President Barack Obama has proclaimed December 17th as Wright Brothers Day to commemorate the achievement of the Wright brothers, who successfully launched the world's first powered airplane on that day in 1903. The proclamation recognizes the spirit of innovation that drives American inventors, entrepreneurs, and scientists. It highlights the importance of freedom of thought and expression in fostering scientific discovery and encourages continued investment in pioneering research, innovative startups, and STEM education. The proclamation also acknowledges the profound impact of the invention of the airplane, which revolutionized global transportation and led to advancements in aviation. The proclamation concludes by reaffirming the commitment to push the boundaries of human capability and celebrate those who never stop challenging the limits of what is possible.